Born Canadian, raised Norwegian. Influenced by canadian bands such as Big Wreck and The Tea Party, but also by the 90's Seattle sound with bands like Pearl Jam, Alice in Chains, Stone Temple Pilots and Soundgarden.

I had a rough childhood and fell out of society at an early age. I found salvation in the most unlikely of places. Today, I'm head above water, but still far off the well-trodden path.

DJ Gemini, de son vrai nom Julien Kern, est un dj/producteur suisse basé à Lausanne. Depuis 1993, il est un vif représentant de la scène Techno alternative helvétique avec plusieurs cordes à son Arc. Considéré comme un pilier de la HardTechno en Suisse Romande il a toujours manifesté une approche musicale orientée dancefloor. Souvent invité sur les ondes de la radio suisse Couleur 3 il a contribué à la popularisation d’une Techno plus sombre à la fin des années 90 jusqu'au milieu des années 2000.

En 1997, il crée avec Didier Jordan le label indépendant Techno Lausannois Pyra records un des premiers labels du genre dans le chef lieu du Canton de Vaud de là, né le premier opus "First"


Depuis 1994, il a multiplié les casquettes, chroniqueur à la radio, organisateur de soirées, dont les festivals Short Circuit, dj reconnu pour ses sets hard techno ravageurs et envoûtants ou encore producteur accompli avec son complice DJ Terrorist et leur projet live Pyra all Stars, les deux dj’s obscures font littéralement partie du paysage électronique des contrées suisse francophones.


Jamais propulsés au rang de stars, ni tombés dans l’oubli les deux artistes alimentent périodiquement les agendas et marques leurs apparitions en dj set ou en live act avec ce fameux concept "all Stars". Gemini n’a eu de cesse de défendre corps et âme un style et un mouvement qui sont chers à son cœur. En 1999, Il rejoint l'association reconnue Trock Music Network pour le développement de la scène musicale en suisse, il en devient même le président avec plusieurs mandats jusqu’en 2008.

2008 est une année marquante avec la sortie d’un vinyle 4 titres en série limitée très orienté dancefloor. Ces mêmes tracks seront gratuitement offerts aux internautes par l’entremise du Pyra netlabel courant juin sous le titre de "Pyra 002".


En parallèle, Gemini collabore sur le thème des musiques électroniques à une émission de télévision Free Zone TV, plusieurs apparitions à la Télévision Suisse Romande pour des démonstrations dj et live . Il rédige également des articles techniques pour les dj’s auprès du magazine Hexadance et de feu la communauté Electronism.net.


Cette vocation continue avec des rendez-vous mensuels comme chroniqueur sur la radio FM Suisse Radio Chablais. Il accueille un DJ pour une heure de mix exclusif interview de l’invité, annonces de soirées et chroniques pour les amateurs de Techno. En 2010, il est sollicité pour animer la web radio montante UZIC, désormais référencée sur Itunes.

It is not a known fact, but Mister Softy is born with a snare drum thrusted into his right ear. Far from being a handicap, this rare genetic mutation allowed him to understand the subtleties of Breakbeat at a molecular level. Ever since a fanatic of complex riddims, hypnotic textures and heavy basses, Softy spends most of his wake life-time locked in his illegal lab, cooking a toxic mixture based on Dub, Ragga/Dancehall, UK Jungle, Chicago Juke and Indian hemp.

Marva+Maschin-Klan (mmk)  is strange objects, selfmade /modified  instruments, german experimental noises and elektro .
funded by marva h kuebler in 1988. After beeing vocalist and bassplayer in a few punk / funk /wave bands and a performance artist at several festivals and gallerys he started a solo-project with music, video art and strange stage objects. Influenced by the early illegal underground techno and hardcore clubs in Berlin at the time MarvaMK developed during the beginning ninetys his simplistic "krautrock-elektro" style and played live at some of the most influential music clubs like the SO36 and Tacheles, EIMER and Tresor Berlin. His videos and "weird" stage effects are used in his own shows but they have also been used in several movies and also by other artists and musicians like Rammstein, Bushido and Yvonne Catterfeld. They used MarvaMks work for their videos and on stage. The MMK also produced video DVDs and various CDs and performed with the band Elektronauten in the Feature Film Goodbye Lenin. Many of the older mmk recordings will be available online within the next months.

Ronnie Sundin (b.1973) is a Swedish sound / visual artist currently residing in Malmö, Sweden. Sound and music is a central theme in his art. His works finds itself somewhere in a grey area in between so called experimental music and visual art. His music has been released in various formats since 1997 and after graduating from the College Of Fine Arts in Umeå, Sweden in 2000 he mainly focused on sound works but he has in recent years found himself focusing more on working with drawings and comics as well.

Is electronic music coming to you only when you have tried everything and when you are dreaming of strange sounds without being able to catch them , sounds which do not exist in our saturated sensorial universe ? 
Or is it our natural tendency towards rythms without concessions , towards litanic melodies as if incantatory that puts us into trance forgetful of everything ? 

Guillaume Spitz and Olivier Vallès have been bathed in music since childhood . Their musical collaboration is the result of those ten years of doubts , impetus , breaking ups : a music which gathers together their peculiar qualities and their antagonisms . A framed creative ardour with electro sounds but also trance melodies and very rocky tunes .

A familiar and out adjustment music , suckled with contradictions and obviousnesses .
Like them let you be seized by this music which first curls you up like a ball and then hits you right in the face . A boundless music , inhabited with all the musics , oddly poetic , made of softness and darkness , of languidness and frenzy .

WITHOUT MUSIC LIFE WILL BE A MISTAKE (Friedrich Nietzsche)

Producing 70 bpm bass dubs since 2007 See Also:, Robbing Hood 111, Rhorh, Orh, Lhp & David R. Webb Robbing Hood: producing bass music since 2007 Searching for the perimeter, where the air is thick and heavy. Following the path wherever it leads: new sounds, signatures and catalysts. Absorbed in a sea of sonic intoxication. Everything constructed from scratch. Drums, bass, oscillator waves, reverb impulses: field recordings and found sounds, manipulated and mangled. Accidents and errors feed back in, becoming part of the process. The medium is the method. “An abstract groove scientist, strangely abstract yet warmly funky, whose work isn’t classically minimalist but he's somehow figured out groove on a molecular level.” - 111bpm forum "This unstoppable badman based somewhere out in the Åland Islands can't literally ever stop himself breaking boundaries, experimenting with fresh drum signatures and literally from listening to his music you can tell this man can't get any sleep until he has got some SOUND NEVER HEARD!" - Bass Pon Mi Blogspot

Markantonio is one of Italy’s most accomplished electronic music artists. 
Italy’s Naples region is a breeding ground of creativity that has spawned many of today’s most exciting young techno artists.

With a career that spans over two decades, Markantonio is one of the people who pioneered techno in Naples, and inspired today’s younger generation.
Still at the top of his game, and one of Italy’s most respected DJ/Producers, Markantonio remains one of Europe’s most in demand artists who also has a large following in South America. 

Flying all over the world to play gigs at festivals and super clubs, his underground style us focused mainly around techno, but he is an exceptional DJ also known for incorporating other genres such as house and melodic. His legendary Boiler Room set in Naples is just one example of his mastery behind the decks. 

He is a regular performer at world famous venues like Fabrik in Madrid, Fabric London, and festivals such as Monegros, Awakenigs, Sonus, Toffler and Freedom Festival. Markantonio also runs his own party “Casamia” which is held at the Duel Club in Naples. 

Many also know him for the music he has released on influential techno labels including Carl Cox’s Intec, Pan-Pot’s Second State, Adam Beyer’s Drumcode and many others.
Between 2020 and 2021, Markantonio has featured original music on labels such as Odd Recordings, Say What?, and Mindshake, as well as remixing Kaiserdisco’s “Bipolar Disorder” on KD RAW, plus other top selling reworks including “Euphoria” by Egbert and Metodi Hirstov.

In addition to releasing on other labels, he also heads up his own imprint AnalyticTrail. Markantonio has been prolific on his own imprint, and recently he celebrated the 100th release on AnalyticTrail with an EP of his own music that also featured remixes by Kaiserdisco and Spartaque. 
AnalyticTrail has been one of the most vital labels in techno, and included in its back catalogue are tracks and remixes by Paco Osuna, Spektre, UMEK, Perc, Wehbba, The Advent and Cari Lekebusch. The label also signed early releases from the likes of Roberto Capuano, Joseph Capriati and Luigi Madonna who following Markantonio’s support, are now some of the biggest names in techno.

Born and raised in Munich (Germany), 6th floor, left door; father german, mother polish, 1 younger sister. With an incredible rich background of different styles of music, Daniela has created a personal style that defines her sound. Her sets and productions expand the boundaries of understanding house and techno music to new horizons, proving her uncompromising diversity on the dancefloor.

In 2010 "EllE Routine" won a "QWARTZ 6 Electronic Music Award" in Paris, FR among well respected artists as Laurie Anderson, Gudrun Gut, and more.
> > https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qwartz_Electronic_Music_Awards

After six years playing in bands as singer, songwriter and multi-instrumentalist, she returned in 2008 to electronic music.
Released on Uncanny Valley, Rawax, Chiwax, Cocoon, K!7, Souvenir, Housewax, etc..

Next to performing live & producing, Daniela was for 10 years co-founding and running A&R, events, merch and record label "Parallel Berlin".

In 2021 Daniela founded https://soundcloud.com/dimensionofbeinghuman, a label, podcast series, art and events.

Her track "Did You Ever" was in 2016 featured as closing track on https://soundcloud.com/moodymann313 ´s DJ mix for "DJ Kicks". Starting with her very first release, Daniela´s productions made it into the record bags of high profile DJ´s such as Sven Väth, Laurent Garnier, Ken Ishii, DVS1, Guy Gerber, Solomun, Marcel Dettmann and many others. In 2015 "Feel The Future" was featured on tINI´s DJ mix for Cocoon Ibiza.

Band names can be big. They can be clever. Or they can even be shit. But Dirty Rock & Roll do what it says on the tin. And then crush the tin so hard your ears start to bleed.

Formed from the ashes of North East noiseniks Baby Rattlesnakes, DRnR fuse punk, pop, metal and madness to deliver the best live shows around. They’re loud and very proud. They punch above their weight. And they’re well worth the wait.

Singer Adam found fame fronting the dearly departed Rattlesnakes for three years - supporting the likes of Electric Eel Shock, Quireboys and Tokyo Dragons. But the former basketball pro was always happiest crunching up Foos-style riffs with his rumbling vocals. In fact classic rock was never his cup of tea, so forming DRnR was the natural move for one of the region’s most imposing musos.

Surrounding himself with a rhythm section tighter than Metallica’s band security, Adam unearthed a killer combo. And if you don’t believe the hype then don’t tell Lee (bass) and Steve (drums). They’ll kick your arse from here to Blyth and back. Really. Tattooed millionaire Lee might look skinner than a lamppost but he rattles out some heavy shit. And if tub thumper Steve doesn’t cause his battered kit to collapse then it’s just not a DRnR gig.

The New Year means a new focus for one of Tyneside’s best kept secrets. In 2009 expect new tunes, a new attitude and even a new album. Expect DRnR to take it to the next level. Or demand a refund.

Italian-born producer Dino Sabatini is an artist whose strong body of work has helped to develop his local scene, and redefine what it means to work with electronic music in the 21st century: though his sounds are completely modern, synthesized and rendered with crystal clear production, he continues to tend the deep roots of lost wisdom and mythology that have sustained human creativity for millenia. The name of his personal label Outis, for example, is taken from none other than Homer’s Odyssey (OYTIΣ, literally meaning “no one,” was the pseudonym that Odysseus used to succeed in his infamous deception of the cyclops Polyphemus). This choice of name is not just a clever title for Sabatini’s label, but is a very good indicator of his own character: working within the anonymous electric wilderness of techno, Sabatini continually goes beyond expectations by bringing the senses back into this world of automation and machines,, occasionally invoking the names of the old gods (Poseidon) or goddesses / muses (Mnemosyne) along the way. Along with the work released on the Outis label, Sabatini has been a reliable fixture on labels like Stroboscopic Artefacts, Elettronica Romana (home to several releases by his ‘Modern Heads’ duo with Gianluca Meloni), Adam X’s Sonic Groove, and Prologue. Listeners familiar with these labels’ respective approaches will understand the kind of versatility it takes to record for each one without sacrificing one’s ‘trademark’ sound in the process. In just the past few years, Sabatini has issued sonic statements characterized by sensations of pulsating darkness (2011’s Small steps EP on Sonic Groove), by intense and penetrating hypnotic effects (both the critically acclaimed Daughters of Phorcys EPs on Prologue, 2010), and of course by the cinematic full-length adventure Shaman’s Path (also on Prologue, 2012). The latter, a fully developed concept album dedicated to those musically gifted guides who take us beyond objective reality into more mysterious realms, is as diverse in its sonic details as the rainforest is in biological forms, weaving a many-colored tapestry of sound around its patient, insistent trance rhythms. Not content with even this high level of inspired eclecticism, Sabatini’s new Omonimo LP shows he is capable of sublime romance, featuring graceful collaborations with jazz pianist Antonello Salis. Speaking of collaborations, Sabatini’s quest for a world without self-imposed creative limitations has earned him an impressive number of alliances: again, the Modern Heads team has helped to expand the vocabulary of international techno, as have his production pairings and remixes involving artists such as Claudio PRC, Donato Dozzy, Giorgio Gigli, Shapednoise, Edit Select and Teste. When it’s all pieced together, Sabatini’s still evolving career is like Mircea Eliade’s description of the shaman’s music: “narrat[ing] ecstatic journeys to the sky and dangerous descents to the underworld” – and bringing back something meaningful and lasting from both.

Lucky Devil Music was formed as a collective in 2001 by four likeminded individuals who wanted to put on some parties, make music and share their love for music.
    
    History
    All inspired by the innovation and originality of the Drum & Bass scene in the mid to late nineties, we set out to reinforce the diversity of the genre by recognising not just the music out there now, but also the funk, soul, jazz, rock, hip hop and multiple styles that have influenced it over the years. So we put on parties in Hoxton, the West End and South London championing this idea and giving people a chance to listen to music from the past, present and future. 
    As our members grew and developed we all branched off into different directions; Ayah pursued her singing career and formed a 5-piece funk/soul outfit called Slinkyfix, Matt Impact continued to DJ regularly on Rude FM, and decided to form his own label, Revolution Recordings, Guy Nautilus worked in music PR, as a journalist for ATM, Knowledge and Jockey Slut while also playing on Rude FM for 5 years, and Jon Baker pursued a career in Entertainments Law.
    As Revolution Recordings gained momentum and support and developed a reputation for putting out music of consistent quality, we felt the need to launch a new imprint which gave us more scope for diversity. Lucky Devil Recordings was launched in 2006 with a 12” from rising star Alix Perez and newcomer Switch and received a warm welcome from a wide spectrum of DJs and punters. 
    At the moment LDM is being run across the oceans as Guy is based in India and Matt and Ayah remain in the UK. Guy is studying Indian culture and music and researching in the Himalayas whilst working for an NGO, and there will undoubtedly be some eastern influences emerging on LDM releases in the future. Ayah is currently touring with her brand new material and you can catch her live in and around the UK regularly.
    Revolution is about to hit release 20 and Lucky Devil is continuing to garner support and release only the choicest of cuts, whilst looking for artists to sign on a long term basis.

Alt-rock artist Rise Bailey Rise has been described as sounding like Beck busking with Thom Yorke and Billy Corgan on the London Underground. Rich’s songwriting is influenced by the sharp pop-songcraft, otherworldly electronic textures, and beats of New Order, Depeche Mode, Human League, and other 1980s UK pop. Alongside these influences, Rich was enamored with Seattle’s angsty 1990s scene, including bands such as Pearl Jam, Nirvana, Alice in Chains, and edgy alternative artists like Radiohead and NIN. Rise Bailey Rise features lyrics brimming with vulnerability, veiled cultural references, layered meanings, and dark-sided explorations. The project’s curious moniker is pinched from the initials of his children plus a nickname given to him.  

Rich’s rise in music is intriguing—no one in is his family was musically inclined, and he never had formal lessons. Yet, he was destined to be a songwriter/artist. Rich’s immediate instinct upon getting a guitar was to write songs, and, armed with a 4-track cassette recorder, he spent his teen years writing. His shyness kept music a private pursuit, though, and he was basically coaxed into joining his first band.

Undoubtedly one of Plymouth’s most established and skilled techno DJs, Calrek has been a prominent feature of the underground techno scene since the mid nineties. Combining his love of quality music and technical knowledge, he has brought true underground techno to his home city of Plymouth. 
Initially working as a roadie for a rhythm and blues band, Calrek's first attempt at live musical performance was playing the electric guitar for several local heavy metal bands. He quickly progressed to manning the sound desk for outdoor events and club nights. During this time Calrek had regular dealings with our other DJs, event promoters, producers and professionals within the sound industry. Calrek gained valuable experience, and always acknowledged the importance of well produced music and finely tuned sound equipment in a club setting. Having had first his hand experience of the Plymouth club circuit, it became apparent that the scene was crying out for a regular, quality techno night, and so Calrek’s vision of Oorpi was born. The objective was simple - the highest quality techno music with intelligent visuals and lighting in a uniquely created environment, allowing the music to make its mark. 
Calrek felt that producing his own tracks was a natural progression. Oorpi 1 and 2 were soon cut on dub-plates early in 1997 and unleashed on the Oorpi regulars, becoming instant classics. At the time, Calrek set out to make the Oorpi Techno vision become reality. Several years later, Oorpi Techno, as the event was now known, went back to basics. Discarding the usual backdrops preferred by club promoters, Oorpi Techno broke the mould and took place at the purposely blackened-out Tramps venue at Bretonside, Plymouth, showcasing the professional digital lighting and visuals of Damage FX and Missing Linkz to their full effect. The event also made a positive and lasting impression by incorporating the very best in sound reinforcement audio systems. 

As Oorpi Techno grew into a huge success, Calrek’s mixing skills became apparent. Lightning-fast and nimble, whilst at the same time using a mixer to full effect to bring in tracks with his unique style. Despite his technical skills, Calrek is a strong believer in maintaining the human element. In an age of locked grooves and digital perfection, his presence behind the decks leaves the listener in no doubt that his sets are live and unplanned. From recognisable classics to fresh new material, each tune in Calrek's collection must be high quality techno, or it will simply not make the grade. Calrek’s varied collection of techno cannot be pigeonholed - from tribal percussions to driving baselines and relentless hard beats and grooves, stabbing synths to explicit vocals, Calrek spins them all with finesse. 

Following on from the success of another of Calrek's projects DMTNetradio (which was Plymouth's first 24/7 streaming underground net radio station setup in 2000), Calrek created his own legendary live video chat (known as LVC to his regulars). Often imitated but never surpassed, this ground-breaking app allowed Calrek to interact with techno lovers across the globe since 2000. Combining high quality sound, visuals, and the live video chat, Calrek's website attracts visitors from all over the world. As well as featuring his own live sessions, the site also broadcasts live shows by other European guest artists.

Calrek has forged strong links with fellow techno DJs and promoters across the scene, and as a result he has headlined at numerous large events overseas in recent years, such as the Mexhanika festivals and the Technosphere festivals in Russia and Ukraine. He is a resident DJ for the Technosphere organisation and has performed at the huge Kazantip festival in Crimea multiple times as well as doing guest shows on many global FM radio stations.

North Street West owner, Darren Morris resides in St Leonards on the UK’s South Coast. He is an internationally renowned musician, keyboard supremo, bass player, composer, sound engineer and producer and his CV is a Who’s Who of major Dance & pop/rock/indie productions over the last 20 years and beyond.

Darren is currently touring with Steve Mason and remixing, producing & co-writing for London’s Horse Meat Disco & with Ashley Beedle and Jo Wallace of Ramrock Records/F*CLR Records as part of the ‘North Street Crew’. Recent North Street remixes include Daniel March’s ‘Falling For You’, Joseph Malik’s ‘Take A Left’, Greg Blackman’s ‘Never Trust Another Man’ and Blazers ‘Groove Sequence’. Darren's recent co-write,  2018’s must have gospel house track Sophie Lloyd’s ‘Calling out your name’, resulted in massive dance chart success.

Apart from being long-term collaborator of Ashley Beedle (X-Press 2, Black Science Orchestra, The Ballistic Brothers) Darren has worked extensively with  Tim Goldsworthy (DFA Records, Mo Wax),  Jagz Kooner (The Aloof, Reverend and The Makers, Primal Scream) and with David Holmes on the Out of Sight soundtrack, Bow Down To The Exit Sign album and remixes.

In January 2016 Darren joined the Steve mason band playing keyboards. In the same year Mason released his third solo album since leaving the Beta Band. A unique performance at the Barbican, London took place in January 2017 with Darren in the band plus orchestra. Steve's most recent album, About The Light, was co-written with Darren and the band (released on Domino Records January 2019)and produced by the brilliant Stephen Street.

Darren is credited on over 200 recordings to date. Albums include The Maccabees' Given To The Wild (2012), Massive Attack's Heligoland, Primal Scream's XTRMNTR, Manic Street Preachers' Know Your Enemy, Red Snapper's Some Kind of Kink, and X-Press 2's Make Shift Feel Good. Darren has performed on some outstanding remixes including Stand Up Jamrock by Bob Marley and The Wailers (Beedle), Shock of The Lightening by Oasis (Kooner), Beautiful Day by U2 (Holmes), Pray For Rain by Massive Attack (Goldsworthy) and Rain Fall Down by The Rolling Stones (Beedle).

In 2013,  Darren co-composed the soundtrack with Phil Mossman (ex-Sabres Of Paradise and LCD Soundsystem)to We Are What We Are, a film directed by Jim Mickle. Darren wrote for string section, solo cello and piano. 

In 2010, Darren co-wrote and produced the album 'Mavis' with Ashley Beedle, which was released on K7 records. A whole host of collaborators appear, including Candi Staton, Cerys Matthews, Ed Harcourt, Sarah Cracknell (St Etienne), Kurt Wagner (Lambchop) and Edwyn Collins. Later that year, the album was performed live at The Big Chill with Darren at the helm as Musical Director, on stage with Candi, Ed and Kurt.  A number of the tracks aired on BBC6 Music and Radio 2. 

Previous projects with Ashley Beedle include Yardism EP#1 and EP#2, engineering and performing on re-edits album Message In The Music (Harmless Records). Darren and Ashley are currently co-writing a sci-fi concept soundtrack album trilogy, Afrikanz On Marz, complete with narration by Kurt Wagner and Colleen Murphy. Think Sun Ra meets Kubrick with elements of space Gospel!

Another exciting work in progress is an album with Horse Meat Disco (Hillard, Stanton, Severino and Howard, which Darren is co-writing. This is following on from debut 12" release, Waiting For You To Call featuring Roy Inc, produced by HMD & Darren.

Darren  released an inspiring album, Union I (North Street Studio One 2016), featuring improvised performance  on the Union Chapel organ (Islington), superimposed with cinematic string machines and spacey mini-moog orchestration.

description:
Born in Thessaloniki/Greece in 1974
and started to Dj in 1995 as Dj Petros at Super FM 108 a legendary underground dance music radio station of Thessaloniki after he had spend almost a couple of years collecting Vinyl and practicing on mixing.He is considered as one of the pioneers of Goa and Psychedelic Trance music Dj's in his city and played a major role at spreading the message to a wider audience through his radio shows (1995-2003)
It was the same time that Goa Trance scene started to grow around Europe and in Greece and as he was already involved with dance music such as Detroit and Chicago House & Techno but mostly Trance, he felt the difference of this unique music and culture, immediately... and a special connection that never felt with any other music genre before and decided to focus on it.
His first influences came from the early releases of labels such as Eye-Q records,Platipus,Blue Room,Dragonfly,TIP,Symbiosis Records etc..

During this period he was also a member of Acid Psychedelic's Club crew... a club and party organisation that hosted the first weekly Goa trance Parties in Thessaloniki with international and local guests from 1995 till 1997 and made history that is still remembered even today...so,he was also present at almost every party that took place there and met many important people and artists of the Goa/Psychedelic Trance scene ..such as Joti Shidhu, Max Etnica,Chakra,Elysium,Edi Mis,Mike Maguire and many others... who have been a great source of inspiration for him.
Pretty soon after his beginning on the radio in 1995  he started playing at Goa Trance parties as his show was becoming very popular.. and in 1997 he had his first international gig at the city of Skopje in FYROM at one of the first Goa parties of the Trance Experience team (if not the first ever). 
That party was a blast and he became popular there as well..interviewed on TV and on the Radio and played at several parties as a guest from 1997 till 2000.

Also in 1997-1998 he was voted as the Best Psy Trance Dj and Radio producer in Thessaloniki at Lemon magazine's Yearly Awards during a period and time that readers had to send their votes through post !!!

Since then...and until today......(after he decided to change his artist name to Dj Peter Zen in 2002) he has played at numerous parties and festivals.....had residencies at clubs and bars in Greece ...helped at festival and parties organization...and promoted his own parties as well... also had quite a few international gigs mostly in Netherlands and Germany with Indian Spirit Festival (2008) Studio 80 in Amsterdam (2008)Psychedelic Circus Festival (2018)and PSY-FI Festival(2019) being the absolute highlights.

Nowadays his music journey includes more music genres besides Psy Trance and Psy Progressive...as he always stays in contact with his Techno roots ,enjoys to play Minimal,Tech House, Deep House...and even Lounge and Chill out...
but his main focus is Progressive Psychedelic Trance Music Production especially after his first digital release on Beatport for Blue Tunes rec. in 2010.

During the years he has shared the same stage with artists such as :, S.U.N project,Tim Schuldt,Mark Van der Vlught,Reefer Decree,Vaishiyas,Genetic Spin,Haldolium,Neelix,James Monro,Max Etnica,Anti,Synchro,Ryan Halifax,Freq,Antix,Emok ,Astronivo,E-Clip,Captain Hook,Ajja ,...and many other international and local Dj's and live acts of Psy Trance,Techno and House music.

Keep an eye (and an ear... or two) out, for some upcoming previews of his recent work in 2019 after learning and also perfecting his music production skills..
as they say on radio...stay tuned !

Aaron-Carl
Producer, Remixer, Singer/Songwriter, DJ…        

It is a task Aaron-Carl has done consistently since 1996.  As one of Detroit's most in-demand producers & sought-after remixers, his signature sound crosses genres -- from soulful, gospel-infused House, to the dirtiest ghettotech anthems.

Armed with little more than a cheap keyboard & a four-track cassette tape recorder, Aaron-Carl proved early on that he could hold his own in Detroit's Electronic Music Scene.  When a demo tape landed into the hands of Underground Resistance's "Mad" Mike Banks, Aaron was quickly signed to Banks' Soul City record label.  Even then, Aaron refused to be boxed into one genre.  His first two records were released at the same time:  "Crucified," a soulful deep house vocal, and "Wash It," a cheeky underground club banger.  While both records received great critical acclaim, it was "Down" (an explicit electro-house track on the B-side of "Wash It") that became -- and remains one of Aaron's biggest records to date.

Ron Murphy (NSC Mastering) and "Mad" Mike Banks were strong mentors during that time.  "It wasn't enough for me to write great songs," Aaron says.  "They taught me how to make great RECORDS…" Aaron compares their guidance to boot camp.  "They saw my potential, and wouldn't accept anything less than my best."  He describes, "Mike held meetings with all the producers on the label.  He'd play the hottest tracks at the time, and would challenge us to go home and do better."

When the opportunity came to remix label mate Theresa Stringer's "Round and Round" single, Aaron jumped at the chance.  Though it was very first official remix, it earned Aaron a reputation for what has become his trademark "Wallshaker" beats. 

Aaron-Carl launched his own Wallshaker imprint in 1998 - named after his final 12-inch on Soul City. "Closer" - Aaron's first Wallshaker project, was licensed by Whirling Records (US), but was never released.  His third single, "My House," caught the attention of Philadelphia house label, Ovum Recordings.  The song got licensed and went on to become Aaron's first Billboard Top 40 Dance/Club hit. 

Cementing his powerhouse status in Detroit Electronic Music, Aaron-Carl has remixed some of the Motor City's biggest artists, like Underground Resistance, SCAN 7, Kelli Hand & AUX 88. He has also remixed International artists like Chicago House legend Dajae, Icelandic techno stars Gus Gus, and African jazz great Manu Dibango, to name a few.  Aaron's productions have graced various labels throughout the world, including Subject Detroit, Metroplex, Kompakt, Sirkus and Universal France.  He has also been remixed by some of the industry's top producers, like Ewan Pearson, Doc Martin and Grammy award winner Peter Rauhofer (Club 69). 

Two of Aaron's deep house tracks -- "Sky" (a tribute to his late father) and "Oasis" are featured in the internationally acclaimed House music documentary, "Maestro" by Josell Ramos.

Aaron also holds his own within the Hip Hop community -- particularly among the LGBT Hip Hop circles. Most notably producing hits for legendary rapper Johnny Dangerous, his remix of the infamous "Topsy Turvy" - in which he makes a cameo appearance -- is featured in the Alex Hinton documentary, "Pick up the Mic."

Owning and overseeing the successful Wallshaker Music label plus heading his own music publishing company, Symphonic Storm Music Publishing, Aaron-Carl proves himself as a definite force to be reckoned with - and shows no signs of slowing down.

Aaron-Carl is currently the host of weekly Internet Radio Show, THE W.A.R.M.T.H. SESSIONS, Fridays @ 7PM EST on WARMTH313.COM.

The Roland Stoves (aka The Interzone amongst other monikers) were pioneers in the techno, electronica and ambient scenes from the early 90's. Many recordings were made during the period '91 - '96, and at least three albums, several eps and a full length promo video were completed, but nothing received a general release. 

In the end only a few demos ever made it out of their Moonbase Alpha studio, mainly handed personally to contemporary artists like Aphex Twin, Orbital, The Shamen, The Orb, Drum Club, Eat Static, Coldcut etc. and a multitude of techno DJs. 

It seems that the diversity of styles that were being output made for an unlikely fit with the various labels of the time. A possible release on Aphex's Rephlex imprint was not mutually agreed, Mighty Force (who first issued Aphex Twin's Didgeridoo) couldn't take it all on board, Planet Dog appeared unreachable and discussions with Rob at Warp were unfortunately cut short.. Even an introduction to Novamute from Richie Hawtin led nowhere leaving The Stoves languishing in the wilderness.

The tracks featured here are from a selection of remasters in an ongoing project to resurrect The Roland Stoves from obscurity...

Hazzaro is the moniker of the Hoody brothers Patrick and Steve. They have been making their mark with their unique heavy hitting Tech House floor-fillers. Both their DJ sets & own productions are packed with energy and infectious grooves are the key component which captivates their fans worldwide.

The duo's productions have appeared on highly celebrated labels of House and Tech-House such as Erase Records, Go Deeva, Milk & Sugar, Instereo, Atlantic, Hotfingers, Guesthouse and Pacha Recordings with the list seemingly never-ending.

The duo's quality is further cemented with regular supported from a list of legendary names; Dennis Ferrer, Roger Sanchez, Richie Hawtin, John Acquaviva, Chus & Ceballos, Gene Farris, Shiba San, Prok & Fitch, Riva Starr, Sonny Fodera, Mat.Joe, Chis Lake, Raumakustik, Eli Brown, Pirupa and Davide Squillace.

Patrick & Steve are understandably in demand which has seen them to play at internationally renowned festivals and venues; Ultra Music Festival Miami, Burning Man Festival, Big Bang Festival, Club Spark 101, Club Mass, Club Sabotage, Club Mekka, Nowhere Lounge Miami, Club Temple San Francisco, Proud Bird Festival and Freight House.

Their Remix of Queen of the Disco on PP Music securing the Number One spot on Beatport for a period of more than eight weeks and was also supported and played by hevyweight names Thomas Bangalter (Daft Punk), Bob Sinclar, Martin Solveig, Eric Morillo, Roger Sanchez, Mark Knight, Robbie Rivera, Umek and many others.

They returned in 2018 with a statement of intent with the highly acclaimed track 'Make My Day' reaching Number Two in the overall Beatport Top 100 for a period of four weeks and several months on still floating around in the Charts proving its quality. Whilst also receiving huge support by artists such as Roger Sanchez, Mark Knight, Tiesto , Fedde Legrand, Franky Rizardo and Rene Amesz, to name a few.
